    pearls: ["Cold shock (vasoconstricted) = EPINEPHRINE. Warm shock (vasodilated) = NOREPINEPHRINE. Know the difference.", "Dopamine is falling out of favor as first-line: epinephrine and norepinephrine are preferred per current Surviving Sepsis Campaign pediatric guidelines", "Epinephrine-induced lactic acidosis: high-dose epinephrine causes lactate elevation via beta-2 mediated aerobic glycolysis, NOT tissue hypoperfusion. Do not chase this lactate with more fluid.", "Milrinone is the drug of choice post-cardiac surgery (LCOS prophylaxis) but causes hypotension: ensure adequate preload before initiating", "Vasopressin is used at a FIXED low dose (not titrated) for catecholamine-resistant shock: it works through non-catecholamine pathways", "NEVER run vasopressors through peripheral IVs: extravasation causes full-thickness skin necrosis. If peripheral is the only access, use dilute concentrations for the shortest possible duration."],
