      { question: "Norepinephrine extravasates from a peripheral IV into surrounding tissue. What medication should be injected into the affected area?", options: ["Epinephrine", "Phentolamine", "Atropine", "Calcium gluconate"], correct: 1, rationale: "Phentolamine is an alpha-adrenergic antagonist that reverses the vasoconstrictive effects of norepinephrine at the tissue level. Inject 0.1-0.2 mg/kg subcutaneously into the affected area within 12 hours of extravasation to prevent tissue necrosis." },
      { question: "A post-cardiac surgery infant is started on milrinone and develops hypotension. What is the most likely explanation and intervention?", options: ["Allergic reaction: stop milrinone", "Milrinone's vasodilatory effect in a hypovolemic patient: administer volume", "Milrinone overdose: reduce rate", "Arrhythmia causing hypotension"], correct: 1, rationale: "Milrinone reduces SVR through phosphodiesterase-3 inhibition. In a hypovolemic patient, this vasodilation causes hypotension. The appropriate intervention is volume administration to optimize preload before continuing milrinone for its beneficial inotropic and lusitropic effects." },
      { question: "A child remains hypotensive on epinephrine 0.5 mcg/kg/min and norepinephrine 1 mcg/kg/min. What should be added?", options: ["More epinephrine", "Vasopressin at fixed low dose for catecholamine-resistant shock", "Phenylephrine bolus", "IV calcium"], correct: 1, rationale: "Catecholamine-resistant shock (persistent hypotension despite high-dose catecholamines) may respond to vasopressin because it works through V1 receptors independent of the catecholamine pathway. In prolonged shock, catecholamine receptors become downregulated, making vasopressin an essential adjunct." },
      { question: "Why is dopamine no longer recommended as first-line for pediatric septic shock?", options: ["It is too expensive", "It is associated with increased arrhythmia risk and is less effective than epinephrine or norepinephrine", "It only works in adults", "It requires a central line"], correct: 1, rationale: "Current Surviving Sepsis Campaign pediatric guidelines favor epinephrine (cold shock) or norepinephrine (warm shock) over dopamine as first-line agents. Dopamine has unpredictable dose-response relationships in children and is associated with higher arrhythmia risk compared to epinephrine." }
